# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-cloud-armor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] An **application firewall** is a form of firewall that controls input/output or system calls of an application or service.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] It operates by monitoring and blocking communications based on a configured policy, generally with predefined rule sets to choose from.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] The two primary categories of application firewalls are *network-based* and *host-based*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Gene Spafford of Purdue University, Bill Cheswick at AT&T Laboratories, and Marcus Ranum described a third-generation firewall known as an application layer firewall.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Marcus Ranum's work, based on the firewall created by Paul Vixie, Brian Reid, and Jeff Mogul, spearheaded the creation of the first commercial product.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] The product was released by DEC, named the DEC SEAL by Geoff Mulligan - Secure External Access Link.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] DEC's first major sale was on June 13, 1991, to Dupont.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Under a broader DARPA contract at TIS, Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard developed the Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) and made it freely available under license in October 1993.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] However, FWTK was a basic application proxy requiring the user interactions.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] In 1994, Wei Xu extended the FWTK with the Kernel enhancement of IP stateful filter and socket transparent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] This was the first transparent firewall, known as the inception of the third generation firewall, beyond a traditional application proxy (the second generation firewall), released as the commercial product known as Gauntlet firewall.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Gauntlet firewall was rated one of the top application firewalls from 1995 until 1998, the year it was acquired by Network Associates Inc, (NAI).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Network Associates continued to claim that Gauntlet was the "worlds most secure firewall" but in May 2000, security researcher Jim Stickley discovered a large vulnerability in the firewall, allowing remote access to the operating system and bypassing the security controls.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Stickley discovered a second vulnerability a year later, effectively ending Gauntlet firewalls' security dominance.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Application layer filtering operates at a higher level than traditional security appliances.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] This allows packet decisions to be made based on more than just source/destination IP Address or ports and can also use information spanning across multiple connections for any given host.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Network-based application firewalls operate at the application layer of a TCP/IP stack and can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Web application firewalls (WAF) are a specialized version of a network-based appliance that acts as a reverse proxy, inspecting traffic before being forwarded to an associated server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] A host-based application firewall monitors application system calls or other general system communication.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] This gives more granularity and control, but is limited to only protecting the host it is running on.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Control is applied by filtering on a per process basis.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Generally, prompts are used to define rules for processes that have not yet received a connection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Further filtering can be done by examining the process ID of the owner of the data packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Many host-based application firewalls are combined or used in conjunction with a packet filter.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Due to technological limitations, modern solutions such as sandboxing are being used as a replacement of host-based application firewalls to protect system processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Application firewalls are available in various forms, including free and open-source software as well as commercial products.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Starting with Mac OS X Leopard, an implementation of the TrustedBSD MAC framework (taken from FreeBSD), was included.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] The TrustedBSD MAC framework is used to sandbox services and provides a firewall layer, given the configuration of the sharing services in Mac OS X Leopard and Snow Leopard.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] Third-party applications can provide extended functionality, including filtering out outgoing connections by app.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/application-firewall] These devices may be sold as hardware, software, or virtualized network appliances.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In computing, a **denial-of-service attack** (**DoS attack** /dɒs/ *doss*) is a cyberattack in which the perpetrator seeks to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users by temporarily or indefinitely disrupting services of a host connected to a network.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Denial of service is typically accomplished by flooding the targeted machine or resource with superfluous requests in an attempt to overload systems and prevent some or all legitimate requests from being fulfilled.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The range of attacks varies widely, spanning from inundating a server with millions of requests to slow its performance, overwhelming a server with a substantial amount of invalid data, to submitting requests with an illegitimate IP address.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In a **distributed denial-of-service attack** (**DDoS attack** /ˈdiː.dɒs/ *DEE-doss*), the incoming traffic flooding the victim originates from many different sources.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated strategies are required to mitigate this type of attack; simply attempting to block a single source is insufficient.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack is analogous to a group of people crowding the entry door of a shop, making it hard for legitimate customers to enter, thus disrupting trade and losing the business money.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Criminal perpetrators of DDoS attacks often target sites or services hosted on high-profile web servers such as banks or credit card payment gateways.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Revenge and blackmail, as well as hacktivism, can motivate these attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Panix, the third-oldest Internet service provider (ISP) in the world, was the target of what is thought to be the first DoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] On September 6, 1996, Panix was subject to a SYN flood attack, which brought down its services for several days while hardware vendors, notably Cisco, figured out a proper defense.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The release of sample code during the event led to the online attack of Sprint, EarthLink, E-Trade, and other major corporations in the year to follow.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2020, Amazon Web Services experienced an attack with a peak volume of 2.3 Tb/s.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In July 2021, Cloudflare boasted of protecting its client from a DDoS attack from a global Mirai botnet that was up to 17.2 million requests per second.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Russian DDoS prevention provider Yandex said it blocked an HTTP pipelining DDoS attack on Sept.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] 2021 that originated from unpatched Mikrotik networking gear.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In the first half of 2022, the Russian invasion of Ukraine significantly shaped the cyberthreat landscape, with an increase in cyberattacks attributed to both state-sponsored actors and global hacktivist activities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The most notable event was a DDoS attack in February, the largest Ukraine has encountered, disrupting government and financial sector services.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This wave of cyber aggression extended to Western allies like the UK, the US, and Germany.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Particularly, the UK's financial sector saw an increase in DDoS attacks from nation-state actors and hacktivists, aimed at undermining Ukraine's allies.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2023, Cloudflare faced a 71 million requests per second attack which they claimed was the largest HTTP DDoS attack at the time.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP DDoS attacks are measured by HTTP requests per second instead of packets per second or bits per second.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] On July 10, 2023, the fanfiction platform Archive of Our Own (AO3) faced DDoS attacks, disrupting services.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Anonymous Sudan, claiming the attack for religious and political reasons, was viewed skeptically by AO3 and experts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Flashpoint, a threat intelligence vendor, noted the group's past activities but doubted their stated motives.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] AO3, supported by the non-profit Organization for Transformative Works (OTW) and reliant on donations, is unlikely to meet the $30,000 Bitcoin ransom.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2023, the group of hacktivists NoName057 targeted several Italian financial institutions, through the execution of slow DoS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] On 14 January 2024, they executed a DDoS attack on Swiss federal websites, prompted by President Zelensky's attendance at the Davos World Economic Forum.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Switzerland's National Cyber Security Centre quickly mitigated the attack, ensuring core federal services remained secure, despite temporary accessibility issues on some websites.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2023, exploitation of a new vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol resulted in the record for largest HTTP DDoS attack being broken twice, once with a 201 million requests per second attack observed by Cloudflare, and again with a 398 million requests per second attack observed by Google.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2024, Global Secure Layer observed and reported on a record-breaking packet DDoS at 3.15 billion packets per second, which targeted an undisclosed number of unofficial Minecraft game servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2024, the Internet Archive faced two severe DDoS attacks that brought the site completely offline, immediately following a previous attack that leaked records of over 31 million of the site's users.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The hacktivist group SN_Blackmeta claimed the DDoS attack as retribution for American involvement in the Gaza war, despite the Internet Archive being unaffiliated with the United States government; however, their link with the preceding data leak remains unclear.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare claims to have recorded and successfully autonomously blocked a 40-second DDoS attack on 23 September 2025, that reached a peak volume of 22.2 Tbit/s, which would be the largest DDoS attack to date.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare has stated that over 404,000 source IPs were used to target one IP address, and that the source IPs were not spoofed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] According to Cloudflare, this came after several other large-scale DDoS attacks, each consecutively beating the previous record, including a 7.3 Tbit/s attack in May 2025 and an 11.5 Tbit/s attack on 1 September 2025.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Denial-of-service attacks are characterized by an explicit attempt by attackers to prevent legitimate use of a service.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] There are two general forms of DoS attacks: those that crash services and those that flood services.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The most serious attacks are distributed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurs when multiple systems flood the bandwidth or resources of a targeted system, usually one or more web servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack uses more than one unique IP address or machines, often from thousands of hosts infected with malware.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial of service attack typically involves more than around 3–5 nodes on different networks; fewer nodes may qualify as a DoS attack but is not a DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Most of the time, attackers operate from an endpoint that is not their intended target, for example using another user's machine to attack a server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] By using another unsuspecting endpoint if it becomes compromised they can then move onto another workstation within the enterprise network.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] However, even faking lots of users and executing a DoS attack, a single attacker with few computers is still very limited in the amount of traffic they can generate.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacks are from multiple sources, it can be difficult for the host to identify and stop them.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The scale of DDoS attacks has continued to rise over recent years, by 2016 exceeding a terabit per second.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Some common examples of DDoS attacks are UDP flooding, SYN flooding and DNS amplification.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A **yo-yo attack** is a specific type of DoS/DDoS aimed at cloud-hosted applications which use autoscaling.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] During the attack, an attacker repeatedly changes between sending a lot of traffic (which causes a scale-up) and stopping the burst (causing a scale-down as a result).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An **application layer DDoS attack** (sometimes referred to as **layer 7 DDoS attack**) is a form of DDoS attack where attackers target application-layer processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attack over-exercises specific functions or features of a website with the intention to disable those functions or features.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This application-layer attack is different from an entire network attack, and is often used against financial institutions to distract IT and security personnel from security breaches.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2013, application-layer DDoS attacks represented 20% of all DDoS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] According to research by Akamai Technologies, there have been "51 percent more application layer attacks" from Q4 2013 to Q4 2014 and "16 percent more" from Q3 2014 to Q4 2014.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In November 2017; Junade Ali, an engineer at Cloudflare noted that whilst network-level attacks continue to be of high capacity, they were occurring less frequently.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Ali further noted that although network-level attacks were becoming less frequent, data from Cloudflare demonstrated that application-layer attacks were still showing no sign of slowing down.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The simplest DoS attack relies primarily on brute force, flooding the target with an overwhelming flux of packets, oversaturating its connection bandwidth or depleting the target's system resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Bandwidth-saturating floods rely on the attacker's ability to generate the overwhelming flux of packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A common way of achieving this today is via distributed denial-of-service, employing a botnet.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An application layer DDoS attack is done mainly for specific targeted purposes, including disrupting transactions and access to databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It requires fewer resources than network layer attacks but often accompanies them.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An attack may be disguised to look like legitimate traffic, except it targets specific application packets or functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attack on the application layer can disrupt services such as the retrieval of information or search functions on a website.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An **advanced persistent DoS** (APDoS) is associated with an advanced persistent threat and requires specialized DDoS mitigation.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can persist for weeks; the longest continuous period noted so far lasted 38 days.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This attack involved approximately 50+ petabits (50,000+ terabits) of malicious traffic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers in this scenario may tactically switch between several targets to create a diversion to evade defensive DDoS countermeasures but all the while eventually concentrating the main thrust of the attack onto a single victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In this scenario, attackers with continuous access to several very powerful network resources are capable of sustaining a prolonged campaign generating enormous levels of unamplified DDoS traffic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Some vendors provide so-called *booter* or *stresser* services, which have simple web-based front ends, and accept payment over the web.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Marketed and promoted as stress-testing tools, they can be used to perform unauthorized denial-of-service attacks, and allow technically unsophisticated attackers access to sophisticated attack tools.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Usually powered by a botnet, the traffic produced by a consumer stresser can range anywhere from 5-50 Gbit/s, which can, in most cases, deny the average home user internet access.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A Markov-modulated denial-of-service attack occurs when the attacker disrupts control packets using a hidden Markov model.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A setting in which Markov-model-based attacks are prevalent is online gaming as the disruption of the control packet undermines gameplay and system functionality.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In cases such as MyDoom and Slowloris, the tools are embedded in malware and launch their attacks without the knowledge of the system owner.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Stacheldraht is a classic example of a DDoS tool.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker using automated routines to exploit vulnerabilities in programs that accept remote connections running on the targeted remote hosts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Each handler can control up to a thousand agents.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In other cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The Low Orbit Ion Cannon has typically been used in this way.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Along with High Orbit Ion Cannon a wide variety of DDoS tools are available today, including paid and free versions, with different features available.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] There is an underground market for these in hacker-related forums and IRC channels.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Application-layer attacks employ DoS-causing exploits and can cause server-running software to fill the disk space or consume all available memory or CPU time.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks may use specific packet types or connection requests to saturate finite resources by, for example, occupying the maximum number of open connections or filling the victim's disk space with logs.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An attacker with shell-level access to a victim's computer may slow it until it is unusable or crash it by using a fork bomb.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Another kind of application-level DoS attack is XDoS (or XML DoS) which can be controlled by modern web application firewalls (WAFs).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] All attacks belonging to the category of *timeout exploiting*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Slow DoS attacks implement an application-layer attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Examples of threats are Slowloris, establishing pending connections with the victim, or SlowDroid, an attack running on mobile devices.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Another target of DDoS attacks may be to produce added costs for the application operator, when the latter uses resources based on cloud computing.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In this case, normally application-used resources are tied to a needed quality of service (QoS) level (e.g. responses should be less than 200 ms) and this rule is usually linked to automated software (e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Amazon CloudWatch) to raise more virtual resources from the provider to meet the defined QoS levels for the increased requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The main incentive behind such attacks may be to drive the application owner to raise the elasticity levels to handle the increased application traffic, to cause financial losses, or force them to become less competitive.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A *banana attack* is another particular type of DoS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It involves redirecting outgoing messages from the client back onto the client, preventing outside access, as well as flooding the client with the sent packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Pulsing zombies are compromised computers that are directed to launch intermittent and short-lived flooding of victim websites with the intent of merely slowing it rather than crashing it.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This type of attack, referred to as *degradation-of-service*, can be more difficult to detect and can disrupt and hamper connection to websites for prolonged periods of time, potentially causing more overall disruption than a denial-of-service attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Exposure of degradation-of-service attacks is complicated further by the matter of discerning whether the server is really being attacked or is experiencing higher than normal legitimate traffic loads.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If an attacker mounts an attack from a single host, it would be classified as a DoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Any attack against availability would be classed as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] On the other hand, if an attacker uses many systems to simultaneously launch attacks against a remote host, this would be classified as a DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Malware can carry DDoS attack mechanisms; one of the better-known examples of this was MyDoom.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Its DoS mechanism was triggered on a specific date and time.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This type of DDoS involved hardcoding the target IP address before releasing the malware and no further interaction was necessary to launch the attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A system may also be compromised with a trojan containing a zombie agent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers can also break into systems using automated tools that exploit flaws in programs that listen for connections from remote hosts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This scenario primarily concerns systems acting as servers on the web.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers, which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents, which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In some cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback, organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can use different types of internet packets such as TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These collections of compromised systems are known as botnets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS tools like Stacheldraht still use classic DoS attack methods centered on IP spoofing and amplification like smurf attacks and fraggle attacks (types of bandwidth consumption attacks).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] SYN floods (a resource starvation attack) may also be used.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Newer tools can use DNS servers for DoS purposes.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike MyDoom's DDoS mechanism, botnets can be turned against any IP address.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Script kiddies use them to deny the availability of well known websites to legitimate users.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated attackers use DDoS tools for the purposes of extortion – including against their business rivals.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It has been reported that there are new attacks from internet of things (IoT) devices that have been involved in denial of service attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] One such attack peaked at around 20,000 requests per second; it came from around 900 CCTV cameras.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] UK's GCHQ has tools built for DDoS, named PREDATORS FACE and ROLLING THUNDER.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Simple attacks such as SYN floods may appear with a wide range of source IP addresses, giving the appearance of a distributed DoS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These flood attacks do not require completion of the TCP three-way handshake and attempt to exhaust the destination SYN queue or the server bandwidth.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Because the source IP addresses can be trivially spoofed, an attack could come from a limited set of sources, or may even originate from a single host.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Stack enhancements such as SYN cookies may be effective mitigation against SYN queue flooding but do not address bandwidth exhaustion.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2022, TCP attacks were the leading method in DDoS incidents, accounting for 63% of all DDoS activity.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This includes tactics like TCP SYN, TCP ACK, and TCP floods.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] With TCP being the most widespread networking protocol, its attacks are expected to remain prevalent in the DDoS threat scene.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2015, DDoS botnets such as DD4BC grew in prominence, taking aim at financial institutions.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Cyber-extortionists typically begin with a low-level attack and a warning that a larger attack will be carried out if a ransom is not paid in bitcoin.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Security experts recommend targeted websites to not pay the ransom.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attackers tend to get into an extended extortion scheme once they recognize that the target is ready to pay.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] First discovered in 2009, the HTTP slow POST attack sends a complete, legitimate HTTP POST header, which includes a *Content-Length* field to specify the size of the message body to follow.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] However, the attacker then proceeds to send the actual message body at an extremely slow rate (e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Due to the entire message being correct and complete, the target server will attempt to obey the *Content-Length* field in the header and wait for the entire body of the message to be transmitted, which can take a very long time.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker establishes hundreds or even thousands of such connections until all resources for incoming connections on the victim server are exhausted, making any further connections impossible until all data has been sent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It is notable that unlike many other DoS or DDoS attacks, which try to subdue the server by overloading its network or CPU, an HTTP slow POST attack targets the *logical* resources of the victim, which means the victim would still have enough network bandwidth and processing power to operate.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Combined with the fact that the Apache HTTP Server will, by default, accept requests up to 2GB in size, this attack can be particularly powerful.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP slow POST attacks are difficult to differentiate from legitimate connections and are therefore able to bypass some protection systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] OWASP, an open source web application security project, released a tool to test the security of servers against this type of attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A Challenge Collapsar (CC) attack is an attack where standard HTTP requests are sent to a targeted web server frequently.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) in the requests require complicated time-consuming algorithms or database operations which may exhaust the resources of the targeted web server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2004, a Chinese hacker nicknamed KiKi invented a hacking tool to send these kinds of requests to attack a NSFOCUS firewall named Collapsar, and thus the hacking tool was known as Challenge Collapsar, or *CC* for short.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Consequently, this type of attack got the name *CC attack*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A smurf attack relies on misconfigured network devices that allow packets to be sent to all computer hosts on a particular network via the broadcast address of the network, rather than a specific machine.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker will send large numbers of IP packets with the source address faked to appear to be the address of the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Most devices on a network will, by default, respond to this by sending a reply to the source IP address.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If the number of machines on the network that receive and respond to these packets is very large, the victim's computer will be flooded with traffic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This overloads the victim's computer and can even make it unusable during such an attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Ping flood is based on sending the victim an overwhelming number of ping packets, usually using the *ping* command from Unix-like hosts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It is very simple to launch, the primary requirement being access to greater bandwidth than the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Ping of death is based on sending the victim a malformed ping packet, which will lead to a system crash on a vulnerable system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The BlackNurse attack is an example of an attack taking advantage of the required Destination Port Unreachable ICMP packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A specific example of a nuke attack that gained some prominence is the WinNuke, which exploited the vulnerability in the NetBIOS handler in Windows 95.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A string of out-of-band data was sent to TCP port 139 of the victim's machine, causing it to lock up and display a Blue Screen of Death.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers have found a way to exploit a number of bugs in peer-to-peer servers to initiate DDoS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The most aggressive of these peer-to-peer-DDoS attacks exploits the DC++ file sharing network.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] With peer-to-peer attacks there is no botnet and the attacker does not have to communicate with the clients it subverts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Instead, the attacker acts as a *puppet master*, instructing clients of large peer-to-peer file sharing hubs to disconnect from their peer-to-peer network and to connect to the victim's website instead.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Permanent denial-of-service (PDoS), also known loosely as phlashing, is an attack that damages a system so badly that it requires replacement or reinstallation of hardware.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike the distributed denial-of-service attack, a PDoS attack exploits security flaws which allow remote administration on the management interfaces of the victim's hardware, such as routers, printers, or other networking hardware.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The PDoS is a pure hardware-targeted attack that can be much faster and requires fewer resources than using a botnet in a DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Because of these features, and the potential and high probability of security exploits on network-enabled embedded devices, this technique has come to the attention of numerous hacking communities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] BrickerBot, a piece of malware that targeted IoT devices, used PDoS attacks to disable its targets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] PhlashDance is a tool created by Rich Smith (an employee of Hewlett-Packard's Systems Security Lab) used to detect and demonstrate PDoS vulnerabilities at the 2008 EUSecWest Applied Security Conference in London, UK.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service attack may involve sending forged requests of some type to a very large number of computers that will reply to the requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Using Internet Protocol address spoofing, the source address is set to that of the targeted victim, which means all the replies will go to (and flood) the target.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This reflected attack form is sometimes called a distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS) attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] ICMP echo request attacks (Smurf attacks) can be considered one form of reflected attack, as the flooding hosts send Echo Requests to the broadcast addresses of mis-configured networks, thereby enticing hosts to send Echo Reply packets to the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Some early DDoS programs implemented a distributed form of this attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Amplification attacks are used to magnify the bandwidth that is sent to a victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Many services can be exploited to act as reflectors, some harder to block than others.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] DNS amplification attacks involves an attacker sending a DNS name lookup request to one or more public DNS servers, spoofing the source IP address of the targeted victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker tries to request as much information as possible, thus amplifying the DNS response that is sent to the targeted victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Since the size of the request is significantly smaller than the response, the attacker is easily able to increase the amount of traffic directed at the target.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) and Network Time Protocol (NTP) can also be exploited as reflectors in an amplification attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An example of an amplified DDoS attack through the NTP is through a command called monlist, which sends the details of the last 600 hosts that have requested the time from the NTP server back to the requester.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A small request to this time server can be sent using a spoofed source IP address of some victim, which results in a response 556.9 times the size of the request being sent to the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This becomes amplified when using botnets that all send requests with the same spoofed IP source, which will result in a massive amount of data being sent back to the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It is very difficult to defend against these types of attacks because the response data is coming from legitimate servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These attack requests are also sent through UDP, which does not require a connection to the server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This means that the source IP is not verified when a request is received by the server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] To bring awareness of these vulnerabilities, campaigns have been started that are dedicated to finding amplification vectors which have led to people fixing their resolvers or having the resolvers shut down completely.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The Mirai botnet works by using a computer worm to infect hundreds of thousands of IoT devices across the internet.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The worm propagates through networks and systems taking control of poorly protected IoT devices such as thermostats, Wi-Fi-enabled clocks, and washing machines.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The owner or user will usually have no immediate indication of when the device becomes infected.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The IoT device itself is not the direct target of the attack; it is used as part of a larger attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Once the hacker has enslaved the desired number of devices, they instruct the devices to try to contact an ISP.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2016, a Mirai botnet attacked Dyn which is the ISP for sites such as Twitter, Netflix, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] As soon as this occurred, these websites were all unreachable for several hours.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] RUDY attack targets web applications by starvation of available sessions on the web server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Much like Slowloris, RUDY keeps sessions at a halt using never-ending POST transmissions and sending an arbitrarily large content-length header value.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Manipulating maximum segment size and selective acknowledgement (SACK) may be used by a remote peer to cause a denial of service by an integer overflow in the Linux kernel, potentially causing a kernel panic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The shrew attack is a denial-of-service attack on the Transmission Control Protocol where the attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It exploits a weakness in TCP's re-transmission timeout mechanism, using short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on the same link.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A slow read attack sends legitimate application layer requests, but reads responses very slowly, keeping connections open longer hoping to exhaust the server's connection pool.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The slow read is achieved by advertising a very small number for the TCP Receive Window size, and at the same time emptying clients' TCP receive buffer slowly, which causes a very low data flow rate.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A sophisticated low-bandwidth DDoS attack is a form of DoS that uses less traffic and increases its effectiveness by aiming at a weak point in the victim's system design, i.e., the attacker sends traffic consisting of complicated requests to the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Essentially, a sophisticated DDoS attack is lower in cost due to its use of less traffic, is smaller in size making it more difficult to identify, and it can hurt systems which are protected by flow control mechanisms.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A SYN flood occurs when a host sends a flood of TCP/SYN packets, often with a forged sender address.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Each of these packets is handled like a connection request, causing the server to spawn a half-open connection, send back a TCP/SYN-ACK packet, and wait for a packet in response from the sender address.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] However, because the sender's address is forged, the response never comes.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These half-open connections exhaust the available connections the server can make, keeping it from responding to legitimate requests until after the attack ends.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A **teardrop attack** involves sending mangled IP fragments with overlapping, oversized payloads to the target machine.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This can crash various operating systems because of a bug in their TCP/IP fragmentation re-assembly code.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Windows 3.1x, Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, as well as versions of Linux before versions 2.0.32 and 2.1.63 are vulnerable to this attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] One of the fields in an IP header is the *fragment offset* field, indicating the starting position, or offset, of the data contained in a fragmented packet relative to the data in the original packet.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If the sum of the offset and size of one fragmented packet differs from that of the next fragmented packet, the packets overlap.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] When this happens, a server vulnerable to teardrop attacks is unable to reassemble the packets resulting in a denial-of-service condition.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Voice over IP has made abusive origination of large numbers of telephone voice calls inexpensive and easily automated while permitting call origins to be misrepresented through caller ID spoofing.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS can exist even without Internet telephony.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In the 2002 New Hampshire Senate election phone jamming scandal, telemarketers were used to flood political opponents with spurious calls to jam phone banks on election day.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Widespread publication of a number can also flood it with enough calls to render it unusable, as happened by accident in 1981 with multiple +1-area code-867-5309 subscribers inundated by hundreds of calls daily in response to the song "867-5309/Jenny".
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS differs from other telephone harassment (such as prank calls and obscene phone calls) by the number of calls originated.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] By occupying lines continuously with repeated automated calls, the victim is prevented from making or receiving both routine and emergency telephone calls.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Related exploits include SMS flooding attacks and black fax or continuous fax transmission by using a loop of paper at the sender.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It takes more router resources to drop a packet with a TTL value of 1 or less than it does to forward a packet with a higher TTL value.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] When a packet is dropped due to TTL expiry, the router CPU must generate and send an ICMP time exceeded response.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Generating many of these responses can overload the router's CPU.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A UPnP attack uses an existing vulnerability in Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol to get past network security and flood a target's network and servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The attack is based on a DNS amplification technique, but the attack mechanism is a UPnP router that forwards requests from one outer source to another.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The UPnP router returns the data on an unexpected UDP port from a bogus IP address, making it harder to take simple action to shut down the traffic flood.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] According to the Imperva researchers, the most effective way to stop this attack is for companies to lock down UPnP routers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2014, it was discovered that Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) was being used in DDoS attacks known as an SSDP reflection attac*k* *with amplification*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Many devices, including some residential routers, have a vulnerability in the UPnP software that allows an attacker to get replies from UDP port 1900 to a destination address of their choice.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] With a botnet of thousands of devices, the attackers can generate sufficient packet rates and occupy bandwidth to saturate links, causing the denial of service.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Because of this weakness, the network company Cloudflare has described SSDP as the "Stupidly Simple DDoS Protocol".
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Defensive responses to denial-of-service attacks typically involve the use of a combination of attack detection, traffic classification and response tools, aiming to block traffic the tools identify as illegitimate and allow traffic that they identify as legitimate.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A list of response tools include the following.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] All traffic destined to the victim is diverted to pass through a *cleaning center* or a *scrubbing center* via various methods such as: changing the victim IP address in the DNS system, tunneling methods (GRE/VRF, MPLS, SDN), proxies, digital cross connects, or even direct circuits.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The cleaning center separates *bad* traffic (DDoS and also other common internet attacks) and only passes good legitimate traffic to the victim server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The victim needs central connectivity to the Internet to use this kind of service unless they happen to be located within the same facility as the cleaning center.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS attacks can overwhelm any type of hardware firewall, and passing malicious traffic through large and mature networks becomes more and more effective and economically sustainable against DDoS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware is intelligent hardware placed on the network before traffic reaches the servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It can be used on networks in conjunction with routers and switches and as part of bandwidth management.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware analyzes data packets as they enter the network, and identifies and drops dangerous or suspicious flows.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Approaches to detection of DDoS attacks against cloud-based applications may be based on an application layer analysis, indicating whether incoming bulk traffic is legitimate.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These approaches mainly rely on an identified path of value inside the application and monitor the progress of requests on this path, through markers called *key completion indicators*.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In essence, these techniques are statistical methods of assessing the behavior of incoming requests to detect if something unusual or abnormal is going on.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An analogy is to a brick-and-mortar department store where customers spend, on average, a known percentage of their time on different activities such as picking up items and examining them, putting them back, filling a basket, waiting to pay, paying, and leaving.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If a mob of customers arrived in the store and spent all their time picking up items and putting them back, but never made any purchases, this could be flagged as unusual behavior.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] With blackhole routing, all the traffic to the attacked DNS or IP address is sent to a *black hole* (null interface or a non-existent server).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] To be more efficient and avoid affecting network connectivity, it can be managed by the ISP.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A DNS sinkhole routes traffic to a valid IP address which analyzes traffic and rejects bad packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Sinkholing may not be efficient for severe attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion prevention systems (IPS) are effective if the attacks have signatures associated with them.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] However, the trend among attacks is to have legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion-prevention systems that work on content recognition cannot block behavior-based DoS attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An ASIC based IPS may detect and block denial-of-service attacks because they have the processing power and the granularity to analyze the attacks and act like a circuit breaker in an automated way.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] More focused on the problem than IPS, a DoS defense system (DDS) can block connection-based DoS attacks and those with legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A DDS can also address both protocol attacks (such as teardrop and ping of death) and rate-based attacks (such as ICMP floods and SYN floods).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] DDS has a purpose-built system that can easily identify and obstruct denial of service attacks at a greater speed than a software-based system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In the case of a simple attack, a firewall can be adjusted to deny all incoming traffic from the attackers, based on protocols, ports, or the originating IP addresses.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] More complex attacks will however be hard to block with simple rules: for example, if there is an ongoing attack on port 80 (web service), it is not possible to drop all incoming traffic on this port because doing so will prevent the server from receiving and serving legitimate traffic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Additionally, firewalls may be too deep in the network hierarchy, with routers being adversely affected before the traffic gets to the firewall.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Also, many security tools still do not support IPv6 or may not be configured properly, so the firewalls may be bypassed during the attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Similar to switches, routers have some rate-limiting and ACL capabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Most routers can be easily overwhelmed under a DoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS using FP4 or FP5 processors offers DDoS protection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS also uses big data analytics-based Nokia Deepfield Defender for DDoS protection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Cisco IOS has optional features that can reduce the impact of flooding.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Most switches have some rate-limiting and ACL capability.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Some switches provide automatic or system-wide rate limiting, traffic shaping, delayed binding (TCP splicing), deep packet inspection and bogon filtering (bogus IP filtering) to detect and remediate DoS attacks through automatic rate filtering and WAN Link failover and balancing.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These schemes will work as long as the DoS attacks can be prevented by using them.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] For example, SYN flood can be prevented using delayed binding or TCP splicing.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Similarly, content-based DoS may be prevented using deep packet inspection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks using Martian packets can be prevented using bogon filtering.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Automatic rate filtering can work as long as set rate thresholds have been set correctly.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] WAN-link failover will work as long as both links have a DoS prevention mechanism.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Threats may be associated with specific TCP or UDP port numbers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking these ports at the firewall can mitigate an attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] For example, in an SSDP reflection attack, the key mitigation is to block incoming UDP traffic on port 1900.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking specific Time to live (TTL) values based on the network path length can be a viable option for blocking spoofed attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service can occur when a system ends up denied, not due to a deliberate attack by a single individual or group of individuals, but simply due to a sudden enormous spike in popularity.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This can happen when an extremely popular website posts a prominent link to a second, less well-prepared site, for example, as part of a news story.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The result is that a significant proportion of the primary site's regular users – potentially hundreds of thousands of people – click that link in the space of a few hours, having the same effect on the target website as a DDoS attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] A VIPDoS is the same, but specifically when the link was posted by a celebrity.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] When Michael Jackson died in 2009, websites such as Google and Twitter slowed down or even crashed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Many sites' servers thought the requests were from a virus or spyware trying to cause a denial-of-service attack, warning users that their queries looked like "automated requests from a computer virus or spyware application".
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] News sites and link sites – sites whose primary function is to provide links to interesting content elsewhere on the Internet – are most likely to cause this phenomenon.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The canonical example is the Slashdot effect when receiving traffic from Slashdot.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] It is also known as "the Reddit hug of death" and "the Digg effect".
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Similar unintentional denial-of-service can also occur via other media, e.g. when a URL is mentioned on television.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In March 2014, after Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 went missing, DigitalGlobe launched a crowdsourcing service on which users could help search for the missing jet in satellite images.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The response overwhelmed the company's servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service may also result from a prescheduled event created by the website itself, as was the case of the Census in Australia in 2016.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Legal action has been taken in at least one such case.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In 2006, Universal Tube & Rollform Equipment Corporation sued YouTube: massive numbers of would-be YouTube.com users accidentally typed the tube company's URL, utube.com.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] As a result, the tube company ended up having to spend large amounts of money on upgrading its bandwidth.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Routers have also been known to create unintentional DoS attacks, as both D-Link and Netgear routers have overloaded NTP servers by flooding them without respecting the restrictions of client types or geographical limitations.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In computer network security, backscatter is a side-effect of a spoofed denial-of-service attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In this kind of attack, the attacker spoofs the source address in IP packets sent to the victim.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In general, the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets, so the victim responds to the spoofed packets as it normally would.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] These response packets are known as backscatter.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacker is spoofing source addresses randomly, the backscatter response packets from the victim will be sent back to random destinations.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] This effect can be used by network telescopes as indirect evidence of such attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The term *backscatter analysis* refers to observing backscatter packets arriving at a statistically significant portion of the IP address space to determine the characteristics of DoS attacks and victims.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Many jurisdictions have laws under which denial-of-service attacks are illegal.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] UNCTAD highlights that 156 countries, or 80% globally, have enacted cybercrime laws to combat its widespread impact.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Adoption rates vary by region, with Europe at a 91% rate, and Africa at 72%.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In the US, denial-of-service attacks may be considered a federal crime under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act with penalties that include years of imprisonment.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section of the US Department of Justice handles cases of DoS and DDoS.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In one example, in July 2019, Austin Thompson, aka DerpTrolling, was sentenced to 27 months in prison and $95,000 in restitution by a federal court for conducting multiple DDoS attacks on major video gaming companies, disrupting their systems for hours to days.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In European countries, committing criminal denial-of-service attacks may, as a minimum, lead to arrest.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] The United Kingdom is unusual in that it specifically outlawed denial-of-service attacks and set a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison with the Police and Justice Act 2006, which amended Section 3 of the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] In January 2019, Europol announced that "actions are currently underway worldwide to track down the users" of Webstresser.org, a former DDoS marketplace that was shut down in April 2018 as part of Operation PowerOFF.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] Europol said UK police were conducting a number of "live operations" targeting over 250 users of Webstresser and other DDoS services.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/denial-of-service-attack] On January 7, 2013, Anonymous posted a petition on the whitehouse.gov site asking that DDoS be recognized as a legal form of protest similar to the Occupy movement, the claim being that the similarity in the purpose of both is same.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] In computing, **SQL injection** is a code injection technique used to attack data-driven applications, in which malicious SQL statements are inserted into an entry field for execution (e.g. to dump the database contents to the attacker).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection must exploit a security vulnerability in an application's software, for example, when user input is either incorrectly filtered for string literal escape characters embedded in SQL statements or user input is not strongly typed and unexpectedly executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection is mostly known as an attack vector for websites but can be used to attack any type of SQL database.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Document-oriented NoSQL databases can also be affected by this security vulnerability.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection remains a widely recognized security risk due to its potential to compromise sensitive data.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP) describes it as a vulnerability that occurs when applications construct database queries using unvalidated user input.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Exploiting this flaw, attackers can execute unintended database commands, potentially accessing, modifying, or deleting data.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] OWASP outlines several mitigation strategies, including prepared statements, stored procedures, and input validation, to prevent user input from being misinterpreted as executable SQL code.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Discussions of SQL injection began in the late 1990's, including in a 1998 article in Phrack Magazine.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection was ranked among the top 10 web application vulnerabilities of 2007 and 2010 by the Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] In 2013, SQL injection was listed as the most critical web application vulnerability in the OWASP Top 10.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] In 2017, the *OWASP Top 10 Application Security Risks* grouped SQL injection under the broader category of "Injection," ranking it as the third most critical security threat.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This category included various types of injection attacks, such as SQL, NoSQL, OS command, and LDAP injection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] These vulnerabilities arise when an application processes untrusted data as part of a command or query, potentially allowing attackers to execute unintended actions or gain unauthorized access to data.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] By 2021, injection remained a widespread issue, detected in 94% of analyzed applications, with reported incidence rates reaching up to 19%.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] That year’s *OWASP Top 10* further expanded the definition of injection vulnerabilities to include attacks targeting Object Relational Mapping (ORM) systems, Expression Language (EL), and Object Graph Navigation Library (OGNL).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] To address these risks, OWASP recommends strategies such as using secure APIs, parameterized queries, input validation, and escaping special characters to prevent malicious data from being executed as part of a query.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection is a common security vulnerability that arises from letting attacker-supplied data become SQL code.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This happens when programmers assemble SQL queries either by string interpolation or by concatenating SQL commands with user supplied data.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Therefore, injection relies on the fact that SQL statements consist of both data used by the SQL statement and commands that control how the SQL statement is executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] For example, in the SQL statement `select * from person where name = 'susan' and age = 2` the string '`susan`' is data and the fragment `and age = 2` is an example of a command (the value `2` is also data in this example).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection occurs when specially crafted user input is processed by the receiving program in a way that allows the input to exit a data context and enter a command context.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This allows the attacker to alter the structure of the SQL statement which is executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] As a simple example, imagine that the data '`susan`' in the above statement was provided by user input.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The user entered the string '`susan`' (without the apostrophes) in a web form text entry field, and the program used string concatenation statements to form the above SQL statement from the three fragments `select * from person where name='`, the user input of '`susan`', and `' and age = 2`.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Now imagine that instead of entering '`susan`' the attacker entered `' or 1=1; --`.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The program will use the same string concatenation approach with the 3 fragments of `select * from person where name='`, the user input of `' or 1=1; --`, and `' and age = 2` and construct the statement `select * from person where name='' or 1=1; --' and age = 2`.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Many databases will ignore the text after the '--' string as this denotes a comment.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The structure of the SQL command is now `select * from person where name='' or 1=1;` and this will select all person rows rather than just those named 'susan' whose age is 2.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The attacker has managed to craft a data string which exits the data context and entered a command context.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Although the root cause of all SQL injections is the same, there are different techniques to exploit it.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This SQL code is designed to pull up the records of the specified username from its table of users.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] However, if the "userName" variable is crafted in a specific way by a malicious user, the SQL statement may do more than the code author intended.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] or using comments to even block the rest of the query (there are three types of SQL comments).
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] If this code were to be used in authentication procedure then this example could be used to force the selection of every data field (*) from *all* users rather than from one specific user name as the coder intended, because the evaluation of '1'='1' is always true.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] While most SQL server implementations allow multiple statements to be executed with one call in this way, some SQL APIs such as PHP's `mysql_query()` function do not allow this for security reasons.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This prevents attackers from injecting entirely separate queries, but doesn't stop them from modifying queries.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Blind SQL injection is used when a web application is vulnerable to a SQL injection, but the results of the injection are not visible to the attacker.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The page with the vulnerability may not be one that displays data but will display differently depending on the results of a logical statement injected into the legitimate SQL statement called for that page.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This type of attack has traditionally been considered time-intensive because a new statement needed to be crafted for each bit recovered, and depending on its structure, the attack may consist of many unsuccessful requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Recent advancements have allowed each request to recover multiple bits, with no unsuccessful requests, allowing for more consistent and efficient extraction.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] There are several tools that can automate these attacks once the location of the vulnerability and the target information has been established.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] One type of blind SQL injection forces the database to evaluate a logical statement on an ordinary application screen.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] As an example, a book review website uses a query string to determine which book review to display.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] from which it would populate the review page with data from the review with ID 5, stored in the table bookreviews.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The query happens completely on the server; the user does not know the names of the database, table, or fields, nor does the user know the query string.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The user only sees that the above URL returns a book review.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The hacker can continue to use code within query strings to achieve their goal directly, or to glean more information from the server in hopes of discovering another avenue of attack.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Second-order SQL injection occurs when an application only guards its SQL against immediate user input, but has a less strict policy when dealing with data already stored in the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Therefore, although such application would manage to safely process the user input and store it without issue, it would store the malicious SQL statement as well.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Then, when another part of that application would use that data in a query that isn't protected from SQL injection, this malicious statement might get executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This attack requires more knowledge of how submitted values are later used.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Automated web application security scanners would not easily detect this type of SQL injection and may need to be manually instructed where to check for evidence that it is being attempted.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] In order to protect from this kind of attack, all SQL processing must be uniformly secure, despite the data source.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] SQL injection is a well-known attack that can be mitigated with established security measures.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] However, a 2015 cyberattack on British telecommunications company TalkTalk exploited an SQL injection vulnerability, compromising the personal data of approximately 400,000 customers.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The *BBC* reported that security experts expressed surprise that a major company remained vulnerable to such an exploit.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] A variety of defensive measures exist to mitigate SQL injection risks by preventing attackers from injecting malicious SQL code into database queries.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Core mitigation strategies, as outlined by OWASP, include parameterized queries, input validation, and least privilege access controls, which limit the ability of user input to alter SQL queries and execute unintended commands.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] In addition to preventive measures, detection techniques help identify potential SQL injection attempts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Methods such as pattern matching, software testing, and grammar analysis examine query structures and user inputs to detect irregularities that may indicate an injection attempt.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Most development platforms support parameterized statements, also known as placeholders or bind variables, to securely handle user input instead of embedding it in SQL queries.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] These placeholders store only values of a defined type, preventing input from altering the query structure.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] As a result, SQL injection attempts are processed as unexpected input rather than executable code.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] With parametrized queries, SQL code remains separate from user input, and each parameter is passed as a distinct value, preventing it from being interpreted as part of the SQL statement.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Allow-list input validation ensures that only explicitly defined inputs are accepted, reducing the risk of injection attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Unlike deny-lists, which attempt to block known malicious patterns but can be bypassed, allow-lists specify valid input and reject everything else.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] This approach is particularly effective for structured data, such as dates and email addresses, where strict validation rules can be applied.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] While input validation alone does not prevent SQL injection and other attacks, it can act as an additional safeguard by identifying and filtering unauthorized input before it reaches an SQL query.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] According to OWASP, the principle of least privilege helps mitigate SQL injection risks by ensuring database accounts have only the minimum permissions necessary.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Read-only accounts should not have modification privileges, and application accounts should never have administrative access.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Restricting database permissions is a key part of this approach, as limiting access to system tables and restricting user roles can reduce the risk of SQL injection attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Separating database users for different functions, such as authentication and data modification, further limits potential damage from SQL injection attacks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Restricting database permissions on the web application's database login further reduces the impact of SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Ensuring that accounts have only the necessary access, such as restricting SELECT permissions on critical system tables, can mitigate potential exploits.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] On Microsoft SQL Server, limiting SELECT access to system tables can prevent SQL injection attacks that attempt to modify database schema or inject malicious scripts.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Object–relational mapping (ORM) frameworks provide an object-oriented interface for interacting with relational databases.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] While ORMs typically offer built-in protections against SQL injection, they can still be vulnerable if not properly implemented.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Some ORM-generated queries may allow unsanitized input, leading to injection risks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Additionally, many ORMs allow developers to execute raw SQL queries, which if improperly handled can introduce SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] String escaping is generally discouraged as a primary defense against SQL injection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] OWASP describes this approach as "frail compared to other defenses" and notes that it may not be effective in all situations.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Instead, OWASP recommends using "parameterized queries, stored procedures, or some kind of Object Relational Mapper (ORM) that builds your queries for you" as more reliable methods for mitigating SQL injection risks.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] One of the traditional ways to prevent injections is to add *every piece of data as a quoted string* and escape all characters, that have special meaning in SQL strings, in that data.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] The manual for an SQL DBMS explains which characters have a special meaning, which allows creating a comprehensive blacklist of characters that need translation.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] For instance, every occurrence of a single quote (`'`) in a string parameter must be prepended with a backslash (`\`) so that the database understands the single quote is part of a given string, rather than its terminator.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/sql-injection] Besides, not every piece of data can be added to SQL as a string literal (MySQL's LIMIT clause arguments or table/column names for example) and in this case escaping string-related special characters will do no good whatsoever, leaving resulting SQL open to injections.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:gcp-cloud-armor/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
